# Axis 23 — shift, not shift0

A deep handler REINSTALLS itself around the resumed continuation — the defining property
of `shift`, as opposed to `shift0`, which does not reinstall the delimiter. So a second
operation performed in the resumed suffix is caught by the same reinstalled handler. Both
operations resume with 11; the second is reached only because the delimiter was
reinstalled, and it yields the final 11. Under shift0 the second operation would escape
the (consumed) delimiter instead.

```scalascript
effect Ctl:
  def op(): Int

def prog(): Int = handle {
  val a = Ctl.op()
  val b = Ctl.op()
  b
} {
  case Ctl.op(resume) => resume(11)
}

println(prog())
```
